comment._content: Originally it cost a car or motorcycle six pence(= 5 cents) to cross, a horse and rider being three pence. Use of the bridge by bicycle riders (provided that they use the cycleway) and by pedestrians is free. Later governments capped the fee for motorcycles at one-quarter of the passenger-vehicle cost, but now it is again the same as the cost for a passenger vehicle. A brief history of the bridge here www.harbourbridge.com.au/hbpages/historycontx.html

comment.author: 35232934@N06
comment._content: The Sam Hood Collection is a wonderful record of a many aspects of Sydney life during an interesting social and technological period (including photography!). I had the pleasure to see the collection on initial Exhibition at the State Library. I found that my interest in photography must have been genetic - and what fine photographic genes these are to have inherited (if somewhat distantly and much watered down in my case!). Sam's son Ted and daughter Gladys were also an active part of Sam's studio among other photographers. I commend the books that the State Library of NSW have published of some of Sam's collection. My favourite shot of Ted's is www.flickr.com/photos/statelibraryofnsw/3447212244/ which is an incredible shot looking through the box cross- section of the Sydney Harbour Bridge as it is being constructed.
